segments.text: Dr. Abbott.
What made him so, what were his character that made him such an outstanding teacher?
Well, he just made things so interesting.
I remember the first course I had under Dr. Abbott was Logic and Argumentation.
And he would have us read articles and
Harper's Magazine or other magazines.
And he said, come prepared to talk about it.
And we knew we should read that article and think about it because he was going to call on us.
He just, he just imparted information into us and made us think, made us talk.
And was just a great teacher.
Dr. Bill Potts, chemistry, was one of my great teachers there, I recall very well.
He was just a very easy going man that, he didn't lecture, Tom Harrington and Colonel Brighton lectured to us, but
Dr. Bill Potts was our lab teacher and our classroom teacher in chemistry, and he was outstanding.
If you had any questions, he wouldn't just go over subjects and say, I want you to understand this.
We're going over it until everybody in this class understands what we're talking about.
And he was awfully good.
Others were Pembroke, Dean Pembroke, he was head of the Bureau.
And he was very impressive and very good, had a good relationship with the students.
Mr. Angel, Lionel Angel, he was more or less the, he would have been more or less student activities.
Joe Skiles, who at that time was a plunder Mr. H in the student activities.
Of course, I did a lot of work with the student activities because I was kind of one of the leaders of the class.
Military people.
What about over in business?
Over in business, okay.
Tom Cherry.
Pop Weinke was an accountant.
Stubbs, B-Bow, Harley B-Bow, they were all in Hagee Co. Tom Cherry was in Hagee Co. Mr. Wheeler-Martin was head of the department, but I never did head as a teacher.
Mr., I'll tell you somebody who was a good teacher also was head of the department, was Mr. Leland.
Mr. Leland was a good teacher.
We had very caring faculty.
What about advisors, counselors, if you needed advice on something?
Well, I don't remember any counselor that I had other than professors.
But I had no problem going to any of my teachers.
They were always there and their door was always open.
I think if there's anything good about A&M in those days, it was the faculty.
What were the, without there being written down, what did you and your fellow students assume were the guidelines for classroom behavior, the rules about going to class?
Well, of course we wore uniforms, and they were clean.
One thing about this college, they had that college law, and there was no excuse for you to go around dirty.
And the students wouldn't let you be dirty.
They'd make you take a shower.
If you didn't, they'd see that you had a shower.
The classrooms in those days, the students were timely.
They were respectful.
They were courteous.
They were polite.
And for the most part, they were very attentive.
Any crowd that you'd get into, every once in a while you'd get somebody that was either combative or a little out of line, but that was the exception.
Do you remember any kind of pranks or tricks or good bull happening in a classroom?
Well, I'm sure it happened all the time.
anybody ever put anything under the lectern?
Well, I remember they uh, what did they do?
They uh, Mr. uh, Dr. uh, D.B.
Colford.
Uh, somebody had gone in there and said, D.B.
Colford.
D.B.
stands for Dusty Butt.
I wrote that on the board.
What was his reaction?
He was the cutest thing in the world.
He turned and said, I may be a dusty bug, but I'm not a dusty brain like somebody who wrote this on his blackboard.
Very good.
He was so good.
And there were other things like that, but right now, you know, it's just... All right, let's go to the run-through, Mom.
Let's go to the dormitories then.
Can you remember some good bowl- Yeah, a lot of good bowl dormitories.
Share some of that.
Well, I was in C Company and we had a sophomore who was giving us hell all the time named Ruben Caperton, best little boy in the world.
He was from Sterling City, a year ahead of me.
He was living up on the
I guess it was the second floor of Goodman Hall.
You know, to get to the first floor of Goodman Hall, you had to go up about five steps.
And somebody knew where an old cow was.
And we got together, and Reuben had gone somewhere.
He was gonna be gone for about an hour or two.
And somebody said, come on, we gotta go get this cow.
You know, I wasn't a stranger to cows.
We had cows when I was growing up pretty much.
I said, OK, what are we going to do with that cow?
And they wouldn't tell us.
OK, we'll go get the cow.
So we went.
I guess somewhere around the dairy, we got this cow.
It was a dorsal cow.
It was not much problem.
It had horns.
We got that cow.
And we got him up to the second floor.
We got him into that room.
And we dressed the head of that cow up.
We tied a lot of old Rubens underwear around it, all that damn stuff.
And we all hid up there around the corner from his room.
He came in, and here he was.
And he opened that door, and you could hear him scream and holler from all over the country.
And of course, after the good bull went off, we had to get the damn cow back down to the shed.
We had a hell of a lot of trouble getting it down, and we did.
And then there was the old trick, you know, of the ketchup.
There's an old guy, I guess he worked for the college, living on F&D Road.
He had a good looking daughter.
The trick was, the thing was, well, this gal, she was having a lot of good sex.
You didn't go see her.
You didn't go see her.
This was the whole thing.
They'd pull over there.
They would knock on the door.
They'd get close to it.
Someone would say, hey, you better run.
Here comes Mr. So-and-so.
This old man would run.
Here this other guy was that was set up.
Somebody shot a gun somewhere nearby.
This guy fell.
And he had a little thing to catch him.
And he spread that ketchup all over his chest.
And he went back like that.
And then they brought the guy up that was set up to look.
Well, Haskell's been killed.
And that went on a lot of times, that kind of stuff.
What about water in the dormitory?
A lot of flooding out.
A lot of flooding out.
Normally, who was the most likely victim of the flooding?
Juniors and seniors.
Why?
What did they do?
Well, they did something back in their younger, earlier days.
For example, I got flooded out my senior year.
So this was a delayed...
It was a delayed thing.
Of a delayed payment.
Yeah.
Now, we had a... Darcy and...
And Jack Henderson had a running feud with some people over at the Kenmore Fair.
And it started out with red ants.
They said, now, y'all got to get us about five fruit jars full of red ants.
So we hustled five or six fruit jars.
and we stole some honey and syrup out of the mess hall.

We didn't have any fire ants in those days, you know, but we went around and found these big red fire ant things, and we'd pour some of that ketchup or that honey around them, or stick that honey down in those jars, and those damn things, they loved the little red ants, and we'd put the cap on a bunch of holes in them.
and would collect about five or six of those things and take over and put in the room with these boys over there in the Kemp Water Fair.
Take the lids off?
Take the lids off and let them, then the, those boys over there, they were pretty good at chemistry.
And they mixed up a solution of what they call skatole.
I don't know whether you know what that is.
It's a concentrated shit.
And they came over to Jack and Dorsey's room and they put that skatole down in the beds, you know, iron and they had open ends.
They put that stuff down in there and they put it in the most god awful places.
Can you recall any of those tricks or pranks which in fact harmed anybody?
I don't know anybody ever getting hurt.
Do you know of university property being damaged very much?
I wasn't in glasses broken.
We went over to Ross Hall and took toe sacks and collected the bats and chimney sweeps.
Nobody heard from that.
We put those bats and chimney sweeps in one of those rooms.
And by and large, the people that deserve to have a trick played on them deserve it.
Yeah.
And vice versa.
And then they got it back.
I mean, it was give and take.
Now, the drownouts.
How did the water get there?
Well, we all had wastebaskets about this big.
And we had a lot of toilet paper.
What we'd do is make up a solution of water and toilet paper all squashed together.
A combination of wet paper and water.
And, for example, Dorsey and Jack had this fellow named Divine that came to visit, like the man who came to dinner.
He came to visit in their room, and he was on the top floor, top bunk.
And he stayed about two months.
He didn't have a job.
He didn't have anything to eat.
He was marching the mess hall just like all the students.
He wasn't wearing khakis and khaki shirts.
And Darcy and Jack just got tired of him.
You know, they said, y'all got to float him out.
Just float him out tonight.
We're not going to be there.
He'll be asleep.
You just float him out.
So we mixed up about two wastebanks full of water and told them to leave.
And Bill ended it.
And we had a kid over there.
He slipped in and he was asleep.
I hit him right on the head with that bucket of water.
And Bill...
Hammocks hit him right down here.
And of course he ran and he flushed and flurried around there for a while and sure enough in two or three days he checked out and left.
What about, did y'all ever make, we used to call them babble bombs.
I never did make a babble bomb.
I put firecrackers in toilet paper, yeah.
Yeah, that was done around a lot, but I never did do that.
But it was done.
Right.
Now, where did you and your buddies go on a Saturday night after the movie for a good time?
Hardlickers.
Hardlickers.
We walked to Hardlickers.
Okay.
This was normally all mail.
All mail.
And what did you all do there?
Well, those of us who could buy beer would buy Southern Select or
grand prize beer.
Now what, you've said those who could.
Yeah.
What did Mr. Hurdlek, did he check?
From time to time he would check.
Ages?
Yeah, ages, yeah.
Did anybody get drunk?
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, there was some time.
Then you always have to help them get back, help them get back.
That was the number one place to go, more or less, off campus.
Except the movie house.
And that was by and large, almost everybody in there was medieval.
Yeah.
Were there any people in there except Aggie?
On the weekends, not very many.
A few of the Bohemians around would come.
Those that did a lot of beer drinking would come in.
But on weekends, there were gals.

that would come in here for the dances, like the sophomore ball, or the junior ball, or the senior ball, or the infantry ball, or the artillery ball, and after the, after the, all the social functions there, they'd end up out, and they had a jukebox.
And they had a little dance floor.
Uh, would there, were there ever any fights?
Uh, there were some fights,
But not as many as you think.
And where could you buy whiskey and so forth?
You could buy whiskey at what we call Jones Bridge.
Highway 60.
Okay.
Go out across the Brazos River.
Y'all called it Jones Bridge.
Jones Bridge.
Because later it would be Whiskey Bridge.
Yeah, yeah.
Jones Bridge.
Just across the river on the north?
On the right.
Okay.
Okay.
You go across the river, and on the right, they had that old bridge there, old iron bridge.
Just as soon as you got across that old iron bridge, back on the right was Mr. Dunn had a bootlegger store.
Did they check carefully on ages?
No, they didn't care.
And it was legal to sell whiskey in that county?
Yes, it was legal.
This was not bootlegged, it was legal to.
And normally the whiskey was it drunk straight or mixed with what?
It was mixed usually with Coca-Cola.
Yeah, Coca-Cola and bourbon was usually what it was.
Then a little later on in my senior year it was rum and Coca-Cola and lemon.
But
It wasn't, we'd have people go and they'd bootleg, you know, they'd say, well, I'll bring you a bottle of so-and-so, but I charge you 50 cents.
Excuse me, I gotta go.
Okay.
Talking about alcohol, did a student bring whiskey, a bottle of whiskey back to the dorm, put it in his room?
We didn't keep whiskey around in our dorm rooms, really.
What was the official policy if anybody did?
I think it was against the rules to have any alcoholic beverage in your dorm room, and so we made a point not to have it around.

Matter of fact, my friend Billy Merrill from Greenville was one of the few people that had a car down here in the early days, and what little booze we had, we kept it locked up in the trunk of his car.
We didn't display any
Y'all went to the clay pits?
Yes.
No, no, no.
The clay pits was something new to me when I came back here.
Oh, that's after the war.
That's after the war.
Yes.
So there was...
The clay pits was not around in my era.
So there was no place that y'all had just to kind of go out in peace and quiet and talk or...
Well, we used to do a lot of walking and playing around at what we called the Fish Lake.
I'll tell you where it was.
It was out around Eastwood.
They had a couple of ponds over there, one of them they drained.
But we used to go over there Sunday morning after we went to Sunday school.
We'd go over there, three or four of us, and we would strip down to our birthday suit and swim in those lakes over there.
The diversity of the student body.
Almost all the students had a nickname?
Most of them had nicknames, yeah.
Most of them had nicknames they brought in from high school.
But then others got nicknames after they got here.
There were some Hispanic students here when you were here.
Yes.
Did any of them have Hispanic nicknames?
Yes.
Were they treated as equals?
Oh, yes.
We had boys from Mexico and Puerto Rico and Honduras and my company, Mexico City, and they were treated just like everybody else.
What about Jewish?
Yes, we had Jewish.
And they were treated just as equal.
Did they ever have nicknames?
Yes.
Was anybody called Jew Boy?
No.
Oh.
Two or three have told me they were, but they did not consider to put them.
No.
Mervyn Hoffman was in my company.
And Mervyn was always Mervyn.
We had, we didn't have a lot of Jewish boys, but the Jewish boys were treated as what was in the manual, not manual, but Manny Rosenthal, who gave the Rosenthal, was editor of our battalion.
We called him Manny.
Mike Hyken from Houston, who was a PR man in Houston.
We just called him Mike.
Aaron Rich from San Antonio was Aaron.
The other San Antonio boys.
But the Jewish boys were not large in number, but they were very well accepted.
Generalize, if you can, generalize about the student body.
Where did they come from then?
Country, towns, big cities, or what?
The student body in those days, my generation, came from all over Texas, primarily the small towns.
They were not necessarily from the big towns, but they were from just widespread.
Rich or poor?
Rich and poor.
Rich and poor.
Did it matter?
It didn't matter.
It didn't matter.
What did matter then for this kind of general acceptance of everybody?
What was the key to that?
Well, leadership.
Leadership.
The young men who could command, who could inspire, they were here, you know.
You could just find them.
Tom Gillis, Tom Ritchie, men that were true leaders.
You know if you're a good leader in high school,
Or junior high, you're a good leader in high school, you're a good leader in college, you're a good leader in life.
And those people, we had plenty of them.
Even though we had a lot of students from small towns.
The students were the cream of the crop in Texas colleges.
I asked this question of Sam Walton one time.
As you look back, did many of your classmates surprise you by the capability you thought they had and what they did with that capability?
Did many fail?
You're saying some did?
No, no, I'm listening to you.
No, I was wondering.
No, what I'm saying is a leader is a leader in Jody.
The leaders we had in our class were known to be leaders in the war.
went on to be leaders professionally or in business.
That's what I was expecting.
And I'll tell you this, I don't know of any, but I guess there were some who did fail, but for other reasons, alcohol or marriage or something else.
But by and large, the boys that were the leaders in the Corps, the cadet colonels and the majors and the outfitmen,
company commanders.
They were leaders, and they're still leaders.
Alright, let's see.
Smoking was comparatively common?
Smoking was something, as a non-smoker, for me at that time, I didn't pay any attention to smoking, really.
But I'm sure
My roommate, Whit Stockton, was a smoker, because I remember him carrying those green Lucky Strikes around with him.
But, you know, I don't think we had too many smokers in those days.
Where could they and could they not smoke?
They could smoke anywhere they wanted to, except in class.
They couldn't smoke in class.
Or the dining hall.
They couldn't smoke in the dining hall, but they could smoke in their rooms.
Other tobacco, did anybody chew?
Oh, yes.
Yes, there were a lot of people who chewed tobacco.
Snuff?
They'd snuff and roll their own.
They had these little, what do you call them, ready rolls.
And they had them in their dorm rooms, and they'd say, hey, come over here, I want you to help me make a bunch of cigarettes.
And we'd get in there and get everything set up where they'd put that tobacco, put those little cigarette papers in there and start rolling.
What did y'all know about marijuana then?
Didn't know one thing about marijuana.
Had you heard the word?
Not that I know of.
Cocaine, of course, no.
No, I don't...
I don't remember.
The worst thing about like that that we saw was every once in a while we'd have an epileptic situation and some kids would have an epileptic fit.
Well for us that was like being having a drug attack because we didn't understand it.
And we had a few kids that we
came to know as being epileptic.
And you know, we thought that was something terrible.
We didn't understand that it was a medical problem.
Getting dates.
Where did the young man get a date?
Well, most of the dates were gotten by being brought in from home town.
And there wasn't any place to put them because there wasn't enough motels in this area.
We'd walk around the campus, the perimeter of the campus, and knock on doors and talk to some faculty member's wife and say, can you keep my girlfriend for next Saturday?
And that's the way we found the department.
Would there be even an offer to pay that faculty member?
Oh, yes, that was the one.
Did they normally accept it?
Yes, they did accept it.
It was, yes, you paid so much it was very minimal.
Did you have some dates like that?
Yes.
And came here on the train?
Came down here on the train or in a car with somebody.
From where?
Well, one that I had come down came from Greenville in a private car with other girls.
And another one I had came from TSCW on the bus.
How did you meet her?
The one that came from TSCW was my cousin by marriage, Harriet Jarrett.
And she lived in Lubbock, but she went to TSCW.
She had me up then two or three times.
I had her down here for one day or something.
And we, there were three or four of those girls in the same group, and I got them a room in J.D.
Pruitt's over.
Now, is the rumor, the old legend correct that sometimes an Aggie wrote a blind date letter to a test seat
using the same box number that he had?
Yeah, yeah, that was so.
Did the Tassie's, before the war, did they come down here as a group?
They came down here in buses.
For a certain weekend?
Yeah.
Okay.
Yeah, for different weekends.
Did that have a name or anything?
That weekend?
No, because it depended on what the big occasion was here.
For example, if it was a senior ring dance,
then the seniors would have to come down in a bus.
And they would stay as many as they could in the old Aggieland Inn.
And they couldn't accommodate them there while they'd just stay at homes and so forth.
Infantry ball would be another occasion that gals from TSCW would come on invitation from the boys in the same infantry.
Now big social occasions, but cotton ball?
Cotton ball.
The ring dance.
Senior ring dance.
What else?
Freshman, sophomore, junior, senior dances.
Oh, okay.
Then there was the infantry ball, the field artillery ball, the coastal artillery ball, the cavalry ball, the signet, the chem warfare and signal corps.
See, all of those had balls.
Normally held in?
In Subusa.
Subusa.
Do you remember some of the great musical organizations?
Oh, yes.
Russ Morgan, Duke Ellington, Boyd Rayburn, the All Girl Orchestra, what was it?
Phil Spitalny?
No, the All Girl was something else.
I can't call it now, but she brought her All Girl Orchestra.
I can't come up with it.
I had a program somewhere here.
Yeah, here it is.
Somebody gave this to me and the others not too long ago.
Spencer Baines, class of 42, A&M Junior Bank Group.
Oh, my goodness.
That's what they looked like.
Yeah, yeah.
And at every ball,
It's Lou Brees.
Lou Brees.
B-R-E-E-S-E. Yeah, Lou Brees.
Class officer, J.B. Hervey, historian.
Yeah, there's all of them.
They're in the committee.
Now, at one of these, if it was the junior, were members of the other classes allowed, or was this for juniors only?
No, it was primarily for juniors only.
but a certain number of the sophomores that were leaders came too.
